9fdab55e-8cce-4c06-a085-df8935931b7a.0a772949-45e6-4eae-a9bc-f659254f08e4.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Generate Run URL - Generates an href HTML link that contains a URL to the run history report for the current run.

Inputs\:
    variablename  - The name of the flow variable where the result should be stored.
Default value\: IC_ReportURL
    displaytext - The text to display for the href link. 
Default\: "Run History Report Available Here"

Results\:
    result - The untagged URL to the run report for the current run.
Example (with default values)\: IC_ReportURL ,Run History Report Available Here

Responses\:
    success - The flow completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The flow completed unsuccessfully.

Input Values\: vm.requester.email - The email address from the prior step result htmldocument - THe email body text from the prior result 9fdab55e-8cce-4c06-a085-df8935931b7a.description=Purpose\: This OO flow sets the reserved IP addresses and teams the created network interfaces on the physical host for heartbeat Prerequisites\: 1. There is an IP Address generated for the HB interface in a previous flow 2. The network interfaces have been added to the deployed servers via MOE Implementation\: The flow starts with the default get user identifier to get the user identifier for the inbound OO user in CSA. Then the flow gets the primary server component ID using the default get artifact details flow. With the primary server component ID the previously created subflow DB_GetDetailsBySubscriptionID to query the InfraDB for details on the subscription. Mainly the check which OS family this server has (linux or windows). The OS family information is then used to launch either the new subflow Windows HB NIC Configuration for Windows or the new Linux HB NIC Configuration subflow. Upon successful completion of the subflow, the flow send a successful update for the process to CSA and exits with success status. 9fdab55e-8cce-4c06-a085-df8935931b7a.e13e2a68-db00-45a1-bee4-55387cc519e7.description=This workflow updates the Process Instance State using PEM API.
